        {
            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Special Exhibition",
            "textentryhtml":"<SPAN lang=EN>\r\n<P dir=ltr align=left>Ferguson has said that he \"paints by faith, not sight.\" <EM>Bahamian Dancers</EM> reflects the intimacy he finds between his religious belief and artistic practice. The painting features three black figures who bang on goat-skin drums as part of the Bahamian parade known as Junkanoo. Ferguson’s use of house paint on cardboard flattens the surface, presses the figures close to the picture plane, and creates distinctive compositions of space, rhythm, and movement. His play with color and perspective verges on a kind of \"second sight\" as he translates the dazzling choreography and musicality associated with this Afro-Caribbean tradition onto the smooth surface of the painting. </P></SPAN>",
            "remarks":"Hold: A Meditation on Black Aesthetics"
        }
